## 2. Comparison: Already Built vs. Planned

Below is a gap analysis comparing the current codebase against the design specs from the PRD.

| Dimension | Current Implementation (`idbi-credence`) | Planned Production Specification (`FinHealth`) | Gap Status |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Architecture** | Client-Side React 19 Single Page App (SPA) built with Vite. | Decoupled Client-Server: Next.js 14 App Router client, FastAPI backend, Supabase DB. | **Structural Redesign** |
| **Routing / Pages** | Local React state (`activePage` in `App.tsx` toggling dashboard, wizard, simulator, and workspace). | File-based URL routing: `/msme/onboarding`, `/officer/dashboard`, `/officer/application/[id]`, `/officer/monitoring`. | **Required Migration** |
| **Data Persistence** | Volatile in-memory state (`baselineCompanies` in `mockCompanies.ts`). Refreshes wipe data. | Persistent PostgreSQL DB (Supabase) storing `profiles`, `scores`, `loans`, `audits`, and `consents`. | **Database Integration** |
| **Scoring Engine** | Mock state generation in `App.tsx` (`handleSimulationFinished`). | Async FastAPI orchestration calling dedicated python microservice agents with a rule-based capping engine. | **Backend Scoring** |
| **Explainability** | Static markdown narratives and hardcoded audit logs. | Math-driven SHAP contribution weights calculated on the backend (`/api/v1/score/explain/{id}`). | **Backend Calculation** |
| **Consent Flow** | Static visual step in onboarding wizard. | Granular consent switches connected to DPDP-compliant consent database tables with audit trails. | **Regulatory DB Hook** |
| **State Management** | React prop drilling + top-level component state. | Zustand stores (`auth`, `onboarding`, `score`, `officer`, `monitoring`) with `localStorage` persistence. | **Zustand Setup** |

